sentence: Stocks posted another day of record highs, with the Dow Jones Industrial Average pushing above the key level of 19,000 and 10 of the 11 sectors on the Standard & Poor's 500 gaining as that index ended above 2,200.
Telecommunication stocks led the rally, rising 2.3%.
Real estate gained 1.8% and retailers propelled the consumer discretionary group up 1.3% with the holiday shopping season kicking off this week.
Macy's ( M ), Target ( TGT ), J.C. Penney ( JCP ) and Sears ( SHLD ) all headed higher.
Only health care ended lower, shedding 1.3%.

The equities' surge came on the heels of the surprise election of Republican Donald Trump earlier this month, which ushered in hopes of pro-business policies, tax cuts and government spending, and it hasn't been much dented by the near certainty of an interest-rate hike next month, according to the CME Group's Fed Watch tool, which put the probability at 94% on Tuesday.

The rally also came amid a strong quarterly earnings season, with 72% of the 477 S&P 500 companies that have reported so far topping earnings estimates, according to data from trend analyzer The Earnings Scout.

The benchmark averages backed off from their highs earlier in the session as a reversal in oil prices and a strengthening dollar weighed on the morning's gains that came after Trump pledged to dismantle the Trans-Pacific Partnership and data showed sales of existing US homes surged to their highest annualized pace in nearly a decade in October.
That helped companies including Home Depot ( HD ), Lowe's (LOW) and Lumber Liquidators (LL) all post gains by the close.
Wednesday's calendar offers few company earnings, with Deere & Co. (DE) and Ctrip.com International (CTRP) scheduled.
The economic agenda has a slew of data due to the Thanksgiving market close on Thursday, including initial weekly jobless claims and the October durable goods orders at 8:30 a.m.

The preliminary November Markit purchasing managers' index comes at 9:45 a.m., October new home sales and November University of Michigan consumer sentiment at 10 a.m. and minutes from the November Federal Open Market Committee meeting minutes are due at 2 p.m.

Here's where the markets stood by the close:

(+) SKLN (+127.88%) Received license from Health Canada to sell the Streamway system and related disposables

(+) BURL (+15.99%) Q3 EPS and revenue beat Wall Street expectations, raised FY16 EP guidance above street estimates, comp store sales increase from year ago level

(-) ATSG (-1.44%) Pilots' strike leads to cancellation of about 75 flights
